<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA36">
<l>muraṇai valitolaitaṟ kāmeṉṟē muṉṉan</l>
<l>taraṇi taṉatākat tāṉē – yiraṇiyaṉaip</l>
<l>puṇṇiranta vaḷḷukirāṟ poṉṉāḻik kaiyāṉī</l>
<l>maṇṇirantu koṇṭa vakai</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Was it<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Is the function of eṉṟē here merely that of an emphatic question mark? Ought this to be understood as a temporal question “when”? One might be tempted to consider an emendation into aṉṟē: “was is not?”</note> in order to destroy the strength of hostility<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">This particular construction that puts the direct object of a verbal action into the nominative and the indirect object into the accusative is a typical Tamil type of cleft sentence, not rare in the Antāti-s; further examples are found in Po. 90.3,4, Pū. 95.1f, 99.4, Pē. 98.4.</note>, once</l>
<l>when the earth was his alone, the manner you asked for</l>
<l>yourself the earth, with [your] hand [that holds] the golden discus,</l>
<l>with the sharp nails that had wounded Hiraṇya?</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
